4 Message Profiles

A profile is distinguished from a base standard in that, through the application of the conformance rules to the base standard, the openness permitted by the base standard is ultimately restricted. Applying this restriction enables implementation of an interface that is based on the profile without needing to make further modifications to the specification. A base standard allows for numerous ways to define a message for data exchange; profiles reduce the number of possible definitions to a manageable set, and their use helps to ensure that systems attempting to communicate with each other implement compatible definitions. It is important to recognize that profiles do not eliminate other possible definitions permitted by the standard; rather, profiles select a specific group from the total set of definitions allowed. In this regard, a profile imposes a constraint on the base standard such that the resultant constrained specification may be used to implement the interface more efficiently. The profile also introduces discipline into the relationship between the interface partners in order to promote harmony in the actual implementation and to facilitate support for a certain use case. Interface partners that faithfully implement the requirements defined in the message profile likely will have a shorter path to interoperability.
Message profiles constrain HL7 messages by adding requirements for a particular interaction. A message profile provides a mechanism for specifying a single message definition. An implementation guide often is created to organize a collection of message profiles for specifying a set of related HL7 v2.x interactions described by a use case or use cases. Implementation guides typically describe broader conformance requirements, such as a use case model, a dynamic definition, a static definition, and application functional requirements. IHE integration profiles can be characterized as high-level or generic implementation guides [IHE TF].
The use case model provides a description of the process being addressed, defines actor responsibilities, and describes a sequence of actions performed by the sending and receiving applications. The dynamic definition describes the interaction between the sender and receiver in terms of the expected acknowledgments (or other transactions such as query/response). The static definition provides a precise explanation of the message structure and constraints for a single message (this is the message profile). Functional requirements describe the application (or actor) level requirements. Such requirements may include how a set of messages are to be used to trigger certain application functions. The message profile’s definition, use, and organization within an implementation guide are key issues addressed in this section.
A message profile can be represented as an XML document, and Error! Reference source not found. shows an excerpt from an example XML profile. Each element in the message profile is listed along with its associated attributes. For a more detailed description of a message profile, refer to the HL7 standard, chapter 2B (Conformance) [HL7 V2.7]. It is important to note that the attributes and constraints a profile places on a message provide a clear and unambiguous definition, thereby facilitating the design, implementation, and testing of interfaces (especially when represented in a computible form) [Sne2007, Sne2009, LRI-2014].
The rules for constructing a message are described by the message framework. In addition, for targeted real-world events (for example, “Admitting a Patient”) a specific abstract message structure (ADT_A01) is defined. The message structure defines a template or format that the message must follow; it defines explicitly the elements and the order in which the elements must appear in a message instance. For example, in Error! Reference source not found., the “PID” segment contains the field “Set ID – PID” and so forth. The usage attribute refers to the circumstances under which an element appears in a message [HL7 v2.7]. For example, the “Driver’s License Number” component in the profile excerpt is required (Usage = “R”) and must be present in a valid message instance. Cardinality refers to the minimum and maximum number of occurrences an element may have [HL7 v2.7] in a message instance. An example of an element cardinality is “[0..1]”, which indicates that the element does not have to appear in the message instance and it can only have one occurrence if it does appear. A table of allowable values can be defined and associated with a certain element. For example, see the “Issuing State, Province, Country” component in Error! Reference source not found.. This element must be populated with a data value that is defined in HL7 table 0333. The length attribute defines the minimum and maximum allowable number of characters a value can include for a particular element. The data type defines the kind of data an element can contain.

Profiling is the process of placing constraints on each level of the message structure. This includes the message level, segment level, and the field level. The remainder of this section defines the mechanisms (i.e., the constraints) and the type of constraints that can be applied at each level.

4.1 Constraints

4.1.1 Usage

Usage rules govern the expected behavior of the sending application and receiving application with respect to an element. The usage codes expand/clarify the optionality codes defined in the HL7 base standard. Usage determines, from an implementation perspective, whether an element needs to be supported. Additionally, from an operational perspective, usage determines whether the element must be present, can be present, or must not be present in the message instance. These rules are expressed from the perspective of a sender profile and a receiver profile independently. For compatibility usage rules for a sender profile and a receiver profile, see Section X.X.

If the same usage indicator that is in the constrainable profile is used in an implementable profile provided by a vendor, the requirement becomes a self-declaration that is read as “has implemented” and “populates/consumes” or “does not populate/consume” for that data element.
Conditional usage for elements is not considered in Table 8.4, because it resolves to R, RE, O, or X usage based on the outcome of the condition. Conditions are used when referring to operational requirements or specific use cases.
In an implementable profile, ultimately only two possibilities are allowed: either a specific element is supported ("R or RE") or it is not ("X") [OemBlo2007]:

4.1.1.1.1 Conditional Usage Compliance

Compliance assessment for elements with conditional usage (i.e., C(a/b)) is dependent on the respective true and false usage code specification. For example, if conditional usage for an element is specified as C(RE/O), the true usage code “RE” can be profiled to “RE” or “R” in a derived profile. The false usage code of “O” can be profiled to “R”, “RE”, “O”, or “X”. The conditional usage codes may collapse to a single non-conditional code if the usage codes are profiled to the same code. For example, if the “RE” and “O” usage are both profiled to “R”, then the usage code can be specified simply as “R” and not C(R/R). A reasonable question is: should the condition predicate itself be allowed to change? The authors are unaware of any standard that provides guidance on this question. An example situation could be changing the condition “if the patient is male” to “if the patient is male and older than 18 years”. Any change to a condition changes the result set as well. In the modified version of the condition in this example, some patients would be excluded because they are too young. In principle, such a change causes the application to evaluate the data in a different way, but it does not change the related usage of this element and, therefore, does not change the handling of this element. It is unclear whether this kind of change should be an allowable “constraint”. When changing a condition, careful consideration should be given to the potential impact on implementations.

4.1.1.1.2 Withdrawn Usage

Evolution of a standard may result in developing approaches for organizing data elements differently, perhaps using a better, more sophisticated representation. Due to such enhancements, it may become necessary to disable old existing data elements in the newer versions of the standard. The process of phasing out those data elements often occurs over several versions of the standard. If the standard makes use of positions to denote the semantics of a field (this is the case for ER7 with HL7 version 2.x or Hprim), an element cannot simply be deleted from the standard, because a shift in fields would alter the syntactic representation. The recommended approach, therefore, is to not permit its further use. Elements deemed eligible for deprecation are first marked as “B” for backward compatible use only. This usage indicates to profile developers and implementers that they are to abstain from using such elements. At a predetermined version of the standard, these elements are marked withdrawn (“W”).
The usage code “B” in a constrainable profile can be profiled to another usage indicator; however, this approach is not recommended (unless it is being profiled to "X"), since the intent of the authors of the standard is that this element not be used in the future. The usage code “W” can only be profiled to “X”, and use of “X” is recommended in the derived profiles (since “X” is implied by the authors).

4.1.1.2 Usage and Conformance

The base standard allows broad flexibility for the message structures that HL7 applications must be able to receive without failing. But while the base standard allows that messages may be missing data elements or may contain extra data elements, it should not be inferred from these declarations that such messages are conformant in the context of a message profile. In fact, the usage codes specified in a message profile place strict conformance requirements on the behavior of the application. For example, the presence of unexpected content for an unspecified element in the message profile is a conformance violation. An example is the case of data being present for a fourth component of a data type whereas the message profile only defines three components for the data type.

4.1.2 Cardinality

Cardinality defines the allowable occurrences for an element. It is expressed as an interval or range. For example, “[0..5]” would indicate that the element need not occur in the instance at all or it may occur up to five times; an implementation must support up to five occurrences of an element that has this cardinality definition. A cardinality definition of “[1..5]” is a valid constraint of the “[0..5]” cardinality definition; in this case, the element must appear at least once and may appear up to five times.

4.1.3 Data Type Specialization

A data type is a container of data and in a data exchange standard can be complex or primitive. A complex data type contains more than one complex or primitive data type. Essentially, a complex data type is a grouping mechanism for related concepts on a very low level. For example, a data type for “address” may contain data elements for street name, city, state, and zip code. A primitive data type is a container of data that indicates the type of data it may contain (e.g., a String or a Numeric value). Complex data types eventually resolve to primitive data types in the end. Data types can be thought of as buckets that hold data. In programming languages, a complex data type is referred to as a data structure (e.g., C) and a class (e.g., Java) whereas a primitive data type equates to normal data types in programming languages (e.g. integer or string in Java).
A constraint applied to a data type is a specialization of the data type (i.e., a more specific definition of the data type’s constituent elements). The primitive elements are further constrained by applying constraints of the conformance constructs. For example, the base standard may define a data type as:

DT_2 is a specialization (also referred to a data type flavor) of DT_1. Once defined, instances of DT_1 can be constrained to DT_2. Other variations of this concept exist; this example provides one way in which a data type can be constrained. It is common for a profile to define multiple flavors of the same base data type for different use cases or purposes. An example could be the specialization of addresses to national (not country, but federal states) or international (country) addresses.

4.1.4 Content (Value Set)

A value set is the set of codes that may be used to populate an element in a message or document instance. The value set is associated with a specific element (which is known as “binding”), and the bound value set should only contain codes that are meaningful for that element in a given context (use case). Base standards often do not or cannot provide the necessary granularity or depth of specification because they are designed to have broad utility. Therefore, the base standard provides a starting point, and it may specify a code system (or, in HL7 v2.x, a table), may provide normative or informative (e.g., example) value sets, or may merely provide a placeholder (i.e., define a concept domain). The process of profiling elements that are bound to code values includes providing the value set definition, the binding to the element, and the strength of that binding.
For example, an element may be defined in a base standard for specifying the “unit of measure” of an observation, and the vocabulary binding of that element is to the UCUM (Unified Code for Units of Measure) code system. A given use case may restrict an element that conveys observation data to (only) a patient’s height, and thus profiling would entail creating a value set containing desired codes related to units of measure appropriate for height that are provided in the UCUM code system. Table 7.9 illustrates an example of a value set constrained for height observations; four codes are selected from the hundreds of available UCUM codes. This set, along with a normative binding to an element defines the requirements for an implementation (i.e., the implementation shall support this set and only this set for this element for the defined use case).

A similar use case may be found in Europe. Here the specification author may choose to profile the value set differently, e.g., include only cm (centimeter) and m (meter). In this instance, the set shown in Table 7.9 could be constrained to only those two values.
Appropriate value set constraints should define and bind a value set containing only the values suitable for a particular data element; however, often this rule is not followed. A common issue found in specifications is a single value set being applied to multiple elements for the sake of convenience, even though not all values in the value set are meaningful (suitable) for every element. The implementer is left to figure out which values in the given value set are appropriate for the data element in their particular use case. (See [Sne2015] for a detailed description of the issue and a proposed solution for defining value sets in v2.x specifications).

4.1.5 Length

Length is defined as a constraint on the number of characters that may be present in the data value of one occurrence of a data element (object). The definition is system-independent; the number of character is what is important at the application level. The application must be designed to ensure that storage space is adequate to suit the defined length, even if more bytes are necessary to physically store the data.
Length is interpreted as a restriction on an element’s data value, not on the presence or absence of the element. The Length Constraint is generally expressed in the form of a minimum and a maximum indicating the number of characters an element may have. A constraint on length restricts the range and thus reduces the capabilities, e.g., [1..2048] to [1..1024]. In some sense the length constraint is a bit counterintuitive when compared to usage. Usage requires that an application add capabilities, whereas a constraint on length may mean reducing an application’s current capability (as configured). The specific needs of a use case will dictate whether length constraints must be applied. For example, if the length is derived from a specific (closed) value set that enumerates all possible values, the constraint may be introduced by removing codes from the value set, thereby possibility constraining the length). This action may lead to increasing the minimum length (if the shortest values are eliminated) or to decreasing the maximum length (if the longest values are eliminated), so a narrower range for length could be specified.

4.1.6 Conformance Statement (Predicate Constraint)

A conformance statement (also referred to as a predicate constraint) is in its more granular form a normative statement that specifies a requirement. An example is OBR-8 (Observation End Date/Time) SHALL be equal to or later than OBR-7 (Observation Date/Time). It provides a catch-all mechanism for expressing a constraint that can’t be defined by the other constraint types (conformance constructs). Specific business rules can be captured with conformance statements.
The forms in which a conformance statement can be expressed vary from standard to standard and can appear as a text description or a computable expression. In both forms a specific syntax should be used to ensure that the requirement details are complete and to improve readability for the developer/implementer.

4.1.7 Co-Constraints

The co-constraint is a related constraint concept that is used to express dependencies among a set of data values. An HL7 v2 message in which healthcare observations are conveyed is one example of how co-constraints are used. Such constraints typically follow the form of “if OBX-3.1 = LOINC code XXXXX-X then OBX-2 SHALL BE “CE” and OBX-5.1 SHALL contain a value from the value set YYY” or a similar form. A co-constraint is not limited to use with observations, but appears most frequently with observations. A convenient way to illustrate a set of co-constraints is to present them in a table format (Table 7.10 illustrates an example for Immunizations [IZ-IG14].

Usually the OBX-3 (Observation Identifier) is the key upon which data dependencies are based. For example, when OBX-3 contains the LOINC code 30980-7 (for Vaccine Type), the data type in OBX-2 must be “CE” (for coded element), and OBX-5 (the Observation Value) must contain a code from the CVX value set (specifically from the Vaccine Group). This example shows how co-constraints are typically expressed in HL7 v2. Other mechanisms can also be used, and they are used in different standards.
Co-constraints are defined in HL7 FHIR for resources and in HL7 CDA in the form of templates in the same way. HL7 Version 3 uses the Object Constraint Language (OCL) to phrase co-constraints on the model level.

4.1.8 Data Element Semantic Refinement

Every element has associated data semantics that defines the sort of data the element is carrying and how those data should be interpreted. That is, the data element is bound to a concept (logical meaning). The base standard provides these element definitions. In some cases, the definitions are somewhat generic in nature, because the context of a given use case is unknown. Profiles therefore can refine the semantics of a data element based on the use case. This refinement is in prose, and hence not conducive to computerized understanding, that is, implementers will have to read and adjust implementation accordingly. Best practice is to provide only refined element semantics in profiles, and not to repeat existing element definitions from the base standard.

4.5.7.1 Slicing Using a Discriminator

The slicing type “discriminator” assigns a data type flavor to the field slice (occurrence) based on an evaluation of a discriminator value. The discriminator must be a primitive component within the field. For example, when PID-11.7 (address type) = ‘H’ then the data type flavor XAD_1 is assigned to the field slice (PID-11). PID-11.7 (address type) is the discriminator and ‘H’ is the discriminator value. The discriminator value can have three evaluation types:

4.5.7.1.1 FIXED VALUE DISCRIMINATOR SPECIFICATION AND EXAMPLES

Table 1 and Table 2 below show an example of slicing for the Patient Address field using the Fixed Value discriminator method. Table 1 shows the field definition for PID-11 (Patient Address). The cardinality is defined as 0..*. The base data type is XAD and the default slice data type is set to the XAD_0 data type flavor. The discriminator is 7 (Address Type), which indicates a component position within the field.

The field slice with these characteristics must appear in the message instance and only can appear once in the message instance. The requirements that dictate whether the field slice must appear are specified by the slice minimum and slice maximum parameters. 4.5.8 Components and subcomponents

4.6 Vocabulary Profiling

The purpose of vocabulary profiling is to narrow the allowable content of a data elements that are bound to coded data types such as ID, IS, CE, and CWE. Vocabulary is a term used to describe, in general, the mechanics of defining, maintaining, and using codes to represent concepts in healthcare data exchange. An understanding of the vocabulary principles is necessary before describing vocabulary profiling. A number of key concepts are defined:
Coded Data Element: is an element with a data type definition that supports coded concepts. Examples include IS, ID, CE, and CWE and any data type flavors of coded data type definitions (e.g., CWE_01).

Code System: is defined as a managed collection of codes that represent concepts used in a particular business or technical area, and often also have relationships between the coded concepts. Code systems are developed to provide a set of coded concepts for a particular domain, and they are designed for one or many specific or general business uses. A code system may be a simple list of coded concepts, or it may be designed with one or more explicit relationships between the coded concepts (at least hierarchical, and often many other types of relationships in a multi-dimensional fashion). As an example, a concept domain of “Administrative Gender” can contain a concept “male”, and a code “M” that represents the concept “male” within the context of the code system.
Value Set: is defined as a collection of codes targeted for a specific use. A value set draws codes from one (usually) or more code systems; the result is a set of codes that constrains the possible content of a data element. A key distinction between a value set and a code system is that a code system is used as a reference source of coded meaning, whereas a value set is a specific constraint for a set of explicit business uses.

Value Set Examples: The Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes (LOINC) is a code system that has tens of thousands of observations and is widely used in healthcare data exchange standards to specify all existing laboratory tests in current use everywhere, and very common clinical observations. Two examples of value sets that draw from the LOINC code system are the set of codes that specify radiology study types and the set of codes that just specify laboratory observations. Another example value set that draws from the LOINC code system is the NIP003 value set that contains immunization observations such as “30963-3” for “Vaccine Funding Source”. The NIP003 value set only includes a few dozen out of these tens of thousands of LOINC codes.


Concept Domain: is an abstract notion that refers to a set of related ideas (concepts) that serves to help define the meaning of a particular data element (over and above just the name of the data element). A concept domain does not directly define a particular set of concepts and is independent from a specific and explicit association to a particular vocabulary (code system or value set). The concept domain of postal code (ZIP code in the US) is a good example.
Tables: HL7 defines a set of predefined tables that contain an identifier and may contain codes. A table sometimes acts like a code system, value set, and/or a concept domain depending on how it is defined and used. Tables in HL7 v2 have two types, HL7 Table and User Table. An HL7 Table includes values that must be used if the concept to be conveyed is contained in the table. HL7 Tables can be extended for concepts not defined in the table. A table could also be categorized as a User Table; this kind of table provides a list of suggested values that could be used, or, alternatively, a different set of values could be defined and used. The User Table could be empty with no values suggested, which indicated that this entire set of values must be defined. Tables have a pre-defined identifier—the table number—that helps in managing the tables and in binding them to a data element.

Caution: The terms to describe vocabulary are overloaded and often comingled. Therefore, depending on the context, one term may be used in preference to another. Below is guidance:

Vocabulary: A general term..

Vocabulary Definition: A general term..

Code System: Defines a set of

Table: Is an HL7 v2 concept that; was developed and used before advanced vocabulary notions became commonplace.

Value Set: Distinct from


In the context of profiling, the pre-defined set of tables in HL7 v2 can be used as a starting point to define value sets. In some cases, a table will be constrained (like a code system), and/or extended, be replaced (acting like a concept domain), or may be used exactly (acting like a value set).

4.6.1 Vocabulary Mechanics

Vocabulary profiling is a multifaceted process and consists of the following aspects:
In a specification, not all aspects need to be specified and often will depend on the profile level. For example, a high-level profile may only bind and element to a concept domain. Downstream derived profiles would be expected to specify further.
Binding: is the association of a coded data element to a vocabulary. Depending on the level of the specification, the binding can be to a concept domain, code system, or value set. The HL7 v2 tables can represent any if these three vocabulary types depending on how it is defined and used. At each specification (profile) level, the binding becomes increasingly specific, refining the data semantics of the element by limiting its content to a particular set of coded values. For example, at the base standard level a concept domain may be specified, and at the profile level a value set is specified, with specific codes for an implementation. In profiles, the HL7 v2 tables are often the starting point for value set creation.
Table X illustrates a binding of the coded data element PID-8 (“Administration Sex”) to the vocabulary identified by “HL70001_EX”. The vocabulary definition referenced by “HL70001” reveals the details of the binding. Likewise, PID-10 (“Race”) is bound to the vocabulary definition identified by “HL70005”. In these examples, “HL70001_EX” is a modified set of codes that is based on the standard set of codes specified in the HL70001 table and “HL70005” is used as is.

Binding Strength: indicates the conformance of the binding, that is, whether the vocabulary must be used or not. There are two possible values: Required (R) and Suggested (S) (Recommended). All bindings are eventually required in implementations, and a suggested binding can be specified in a constrainable profile (i.e., the specification needs to be further constrained before implementation). The bound vocabulary definition with a binding strength of “Suggested” can be used, modified, or replaced by an alternative code set in derived profiles. Bindings to concept domains and code systems always have a binding strength of “Suggested”. This is because at the implementation level, all vocabulary bindings are to value sets (i.e., a definitive set of codes have been selected).

In constrainable profiles, the binding strength can initially be left unspecified and set once the use case or implementation requirements are better known. For implementation profiles, the binding strength must be set to required.
It is important in profiles to explicitly set the binding strength to required when the intent is to require a set of code for use. This declaration is necessary to avoid confusion related the implications of the underlying data type of the element the binding is associated with. For example, the “IS” data type indicates that the element is associated with a User Table. But this is not the desired specification in the profile.
Binding Parameters: defines allowable options for code set modifications in derived profiles. Binding parameters include extensibility and stability.
Extensibility: indicates whether the value set definition can be extended or not in a derived (profiled) version of the specification. The extensibility of a value set definition can be either open or closed. Open means that more values can be added to the value set in a derived specification. Closed means that no more values can be added to the value set in a derived specification.
Stability: indicates whether the content of a value set can change outside of the definition of the value set or the specification in which it is bound to one or more data elements. Often the value set is dependent on an external code system that may be updated or replaced after publication of the interoperability specification. Stability can have one of two values: static or dynamic. Static indicates that for this version of the specification the value set is completely fixed, both its definition and the expanded list of codes. If the value set needs to be modified, then a new value set and an updated version of the specification must be created. Dynamic means that a value set can change outside of the definition of the specification (and, thus in essence, it becomes a new value set that may be managed and referred to in various ways). In some instances, dynamic value sets are entire code systems that periodically are updated.

Implementation Note: The CVX code system (used for immunization messaging in the US) or the German PZN (pharmaceutical central numbers) are good examples. A new vaccine may be developed or an existing one deprecated and replaced with another. Another good example is the set of codes used for diagnoses. In Germany, a new code system for this purpose is released every year (e.g., “ICD-10 German Modification Release 2016”). In order to avoid the need for an updated release of the specification each year, the binding to a value set with dynamic stability is established. Under these circumstances the latest version of the value set should be used. How trading partners convey the use of the updated value set varies in practice. In some cases, it may be critical for them to be in harmony with the latest version immediately, while in others it may not be. Without prior agreement, the use of the conformance claim is useful. The Message Profile Identifier element (MSH-21) can declare the value set being used (the value set is a profile component).

The value set definition shown in Error! Reference source not found. shows all of the codes in the code system (A, F, M, N, O, U) and the codes selected for inclusion into the values set (F, M, U). A value set definition may or may not include the complete set of codes in the source code system. The complete set is presented in this example to show the value set in the context of the source code system. Other forms of representation are equally acceptable as long as sufficient information is provided to indicated the status of the code (See Vocabulary Profiling in Chapter 7 for more information).
In this example value set, the usage is limited to inclusion or exclusion. Additional specificity can be associated with the code usage. To understand the concepts of code usage and its implications, however, knowledge about profiling and applying constraints is necessary. Therefore, the concept is briefly introduced here and is explained in detail in Chapter 7 (Principles of Effective Profiling). Usage can represent the exclusion, definite inclusion, or possible inclusion of a code in a value set. The various standards have different vocabulary conformance models where the use and meaning of usage varies. HL7 V3 realizes this notion using the words min/max/ignore, whereas some standards don’t explicitly deal with this idea at all.
The Content Definition of the value set indicates the method used to expand a value set definition into a set of codes. The example presented in Error! Reference source not found. is an explicit listing (i.e., enumeration). An enumerated value set definition is called an Extensional definition. Other means used to expand a value set definition into a set of codes include using regular expressions, characterizing specific attributes for a specific code system (e.g., all laboratory codes in LOINC), or using hierarchical associations that include all specializations of the codes in question. By applying these kinds of mechanisms, a value set definition can be expanded to the Value Set Expansion providing all codes required for the identified business use in the implementation. This form is called an Intensional definition. For Intensional include statements on defining it in the binding parameters to get to the value set expansion. How that is describe or expanded/realized is out of scope here. It could be a call to vocabulary service.
Extensibility indicates whether the value set definition can be extended or not in a derived (profiled) version of the specification. This concept is also linked to the profiling, so it is only introduced here and is expanded upon in Chapter 7 (Principles of Effective Profiling). The extensibility of a value set definition can be either open or closed. Open means that more values can be added to the value set in a derived specification. Closed means that no more values can be added to the value set in a derived specification.
In HL7 V3 and CDA, CNE (Coded, No Extensions) is used to express that only the codes in the value set are allowed to be used for HL7 V3 or CDA components to which the value set is bound. This is similar to “closed” extensibility (but not equivalent). Likewise, CWE (Coded, With Extensions) allows additional codes outside the value set if a code does not exist in the value set needed. This is similar to “open” extensibility (but not equivalent). Note, the CNE and CWE counterparts used in HL7 v2.x convey an entirely different notion.
Stability indicates whether the content of a value set can change outside of the definition of the value set or the specification in which it is bound to one or more data elements. Often the value set is dependent on an external code system that may be updated or replaced after publication of the interoperability specification. Stability can have one of two values: static or dynamic. Static indicates that for this version of the specification the value set is completely fixed, both its definition and the expanded list of codes. If the value set needs to be modified, then a new value set and an updated version of the specification must be created. Dynamic means that a value set can change outside of the definition of the specification (and, thus in essence, it becomes a new value set that may be managed and referred to in various ways). In some instances, dynamic value sets are entire code systems that periodically are updated. The CVX code system (used for immunization messaging in the US) or the German PZN (pharmaceutical central numbers) are good examples. A new vaccine may be developed or an existing one deprecated and replaced with another. Another good example is the set of codes used for diagnoses. In Germany, a new code system for this purpose is released every year (e.g., “ICD-10 German Modification Release 2016”). In order to avoid the need for an updated release of the specification each year, the binding to a value set with dynamic stability is established. Under these circumstances the latest version of the value set should be used. How trading partners convey the use of the updated value set varies in practice. In some cases, it may be critical for them to be in harmony with the latest version immediately, while in others it may not be. Without prior agreement, the use of the conformance claim is useful. For example, in HL7 v2.x, the value set being used (the value set is a profile component) can be conveyed in the Message Profile Identifier element (MSH-21). Unfortunately, not all standards provide such a mechanism.
Vocabulary is a complicated and convoluted subject. An attempt will be made here to provide the basic concepts (in a generic fashion) and insight into the key factors that should be considered when working with vocabularies. Every standard approaches the specification and profiling of vocabulary in a different way; there is no common methodology or glossary of terms to use. The approach presented here is representative of one school of thought and by no means expresses a consensus viewpoint.

Implementation Tolerance: There are certain use cases in which necessitates sending unknown codes.


Note: Extensibility is a concept that allows a vocabulary to be extended at the time of specification. That is, a vocabulary defined in a specification can add codes to the code set in a derived specification. So even though a vocabulary can be extended, the code set is always known to the implementer. Tolerance is a concept that allows for unknown (undocumented) codes to be exchanged at runtime with impunity. The complete code set is not known to the implementers. For binding that supports tolerance, an implementation must process unknown codes without raising an exception.

Figure 7.2 indicates the types of vocabulary bindings that are typical for each profiling level. The base standard level supports broad use cases, so it follows that the vocabulary bindings are more at the concept and code system level. As use cases are developed and refinement of a specification occurs at the constrainable profile level, more information becomes known, and, therefore, relevant value sets begin to emerge. At the implementation level, all coded elements must be linked to a specific value set. In some implementation level specifications, an element is bound to a code system, which is then deemed implicitly to be the value set (although explicit designation is recommended). 4.6.2 Single Code Element Binding

A single code element binding is a vocabulary binding in which the binding to an element is to a single value selected from a vocabulary definition. Through analysis, it is determined that only a single code is suitable for the use case. In such circumstances, the binding is to a constant value and a special binding mechanism can be applied. The single code element binding constraint pattern allows for the vocabulary binding without having to employ the complete vocabulary mechanics process. Below is the constraint pattern:
Constraint Pattern: Element Location (Element Name) SHALL contain the constant value ‘Code’ drawn from the ‘Code System’ code system.
A typical example is for MSH-9 values and MSH-12 (Version ID). The example below is for the message event defined in MSH-9.2.
Example: MSH-9.2 (Event Type) SHALL contain the constant value ‘A04’ drawn from the ‘HL70003’ code system.
The single code element binding is a convenience tool to specify a complete vocabulary binding in a single statement.

4.6.3 Vocabulary Binding and Profiling

Specification of vocabulary conformance is a multidimensional process. It involves successive refinement of both the informational model and vocabulary in parallel. The figure in Chapter 5 labeled as “Summary of Vocabulary Mechanics” provides an overview of these vocabulary conformance mechanics. The ultimate goal of the specification is to bind coded data elements to a specific set of codes to facilitate a precise implementation.
As described previously, specifications are refined via the process of profiling. The labels in the boxes that are lined up along the left-most side of Figure 7.3 illustrate a profile hierarchy progressing from a general (abstract) specification to a completely constrained and precise implementation. Each of the three rows, demarcated in the diagram by the horizontal dashed lines, shows the successive operations performed on both the specification of the data elements and the vocabulary objects with which they are associated. This successive constraint is shown in the diagram starting with the top row, then continuing with the next row down, and, finally, ending with the bottom row. To reduce the clutter in the diagram, this process is shown using only a single example data element that is associated with a “simple” value set consisting only of codes from one code system; but all of the indicated items exist for each and every one of the coded data elements in any profile. The binding of a coded data element is either to an internal value set or an external value set (indicated by “XOR” in the diagram).
The labels in the three boxes across the top of the diagram indicate the three parallel constraint processes by which specification of vocabulary conformance occurs. The steps related to the process of defining, refining, and maintaining the sets of coded concepts are illustrated in the portion of the diagram that is below the box labelled “Internal Terminology Space”. This information applies to those vocabulary objects that are handled by the same organizational processes used for constraining a profile and/or the base specification. These internal value sets may come from the base specification or may be created as entirely new sets for the profile being developed. The central portion of the diagram below the box labeled "Information Model Space" illustrates the processes wherein the profile definitions are created. These definitions include data elements and their bindings to value sets, as well as various parameters controlling use and extensibility (described in detail in the sections to follow). The portion of the diagram below the box labeled "External Terminology Space" shows that the governance processes for these vocabulary objects are handled by an organizational entity that is outside of, and separate from, the entity developing the profile (although some communication may exist between these entities).
One goal of the profile constraining process is to define a binding to vocabulary that ultimately is implementable for each data element that is assigned a coded element data type. This binding is necessary for all coded data elements for an operational implementation, and the binding can be to a value set that is created and maintained within the confines of the profile definition (internal) or to a value set that is created and maintained externally. An internal binding refers to a value set binding in which the code system is defined within the specification (typically the base standard, but the values may also be defined within any of the profiles being derived from the base standard). This value set is created or copied from another internal source and subsequently bound to a data element. For an external binding, the code system is always maintained by external stewards. Those stewards (or in some cases another third party) may create a value set, or they may copy an external value set expansion into the profile during the final implementation constraining process (as shown within the red dotted line in the diagram).
Examples of external steward organizations include ISO and WHO (which define many international code systems), IHTSDO (SNOMED CT), Regenstrief (LOINC), and VSAC (the Value Set Authority Center of the US National Library of Medicine, which develops and publishes value sets for use in implementing the US “Meaningful Use” regulations). In many (but not all) of these cases, the value sets also are developed externally to the profile constraining activity, but they may have some modifications originating from “inside” the profiling activity. Finally, the labels in the boxes positioned along the rightmost side of the diagram describe the sequential activities that are performed on the code systems and value sets as constraint of the profile moves towards Implementation level refinement.
It is important to note that these three profiling activities shown in parallel may be performed independently and do not have any timing-based relationships between them that can be considered during the iterations of the profiling cycles.
A value set is derived from one or more code systems or another pre-existing value set through the process of constraining and extending (this action is represented in the Figure 7.3 diagram by the green stars and green arrows). The constraint and extension mechanism applies to both internally and externally defined value sets, and is part of defining and using the binding parameters.

Figure 7.3: Vocabulary Binding and Profiling: A High-level Perspective
The binding of a data element to a value set is annotated in Figure 7.3 by the blue stars. The specification (i.e., the profile) makes this association explicit. The binding includes parameters that are used to define specificity. This required specificity includes details related to the code system (such as its release version), the requirement to use the codes in the value sets (as opposed to custom codes or free text), and the limits of or guidance on further constraint of the value set for a subsequent profile. These specificity parameters are explained in detail in the sections to follow.
Value set authoring is the initial phase of specification in either of the Terminology Spaces. As a profile is constrained for a specific use case, the value sets are refined to match the needs of that use case. This phase is labeled as “Derived Specification” in the second row of the diagram. The operations on vocabulary during this phase can be described as a “Value Set Modification", where the value sets that were established in the specification to which the constraints are being applied are further constrained (and/or extended); this notion is indicated in Figure 7.3 with the green stars and arrows. Note that extending may involve adding codes from a code system to the value set. The thickness of the binding (black) arrows that point from a data element to a value set box in the diagram decreases in each of the sequential three rows to indicate a more precise (and often smaller) set of values. Note that more than one derived specification may be produced for a set of related or similar use cases during each iteration (i.e., profiling cycle) of the operations shown in the portion of the diagram below the Information Model Space label.
The bottom “Implementation” row represents the implementation profile and its realization (the actual configured system that is in production). In the transition from the “Derived Specification” to the “Implementation”, further constraints (and extensions) may be specified. Additionally, once the value set definition has been finalized, its set of specific values can be realized (e.g., enumerated) through the process of value set expansion. This action, indicated in the diagram by the label "expand()" on the vertical arrow in the second row, is an operation that may be performed manually at the local installation site or by a terminology service that is available to the profile authors, developers, and system implementers. The value set expansion is the code set instance in a form directly suitable for implementation. Note that under some circumstances, a data element in an Implementation Profile may still be bound to a Value Set Definition that has not yet been expanded to an explicit list of values (“Value Set Expansion”). In these cases, the development of the final Implementation Profile involves further constraint and parameterization of the Value Set Definition, so the final expansion may be completed at the time of implementation of the system, and will be deterministic at that time.

4.6.4 Use of Extensibility and Stability

Figure 7.4 shows value set attributes of Extensibility and Stability (See Chapter 5 for definitions) along with the allowable settings these attributes may take on related to the specification space and their impact in post specification and runtime environment. The requirements for value sets are determined when specifications are created initially in the base standard, and then these requirements are subsequently refined through the mechanism of profiling. The specification (and the impact of that specification) of the extensibility and stability for a value set can be considered in three distinct spaces: the specification space, post specification space, and operational space. In the specification space, the extensibility of a value set can be designated as “open” or “closed”. Constrainable profiles (which include the base standard) can specify value set extensibility as either “open” or “closed”. For implementation profiles, the value set extensibility is closed. At this point in the creation of the specification, the use case is definitive; therefore, the universe of allowable values for the element is known and is documented as such. Any desired change would have to occur in another version of the specification with a new value set. Extensibility is a construct in the context of the specification space; modification of a value set outside the specification space is controlled by Stability and is discussed next.
There are circumstances when, although the completed state is known, it is anticipated that additional updates to a value set will be necessary. In some cases, the updates can be managed, published, and communicated in an orderly manner. This situation occurs in the post specification space, and it is indicated by the value set having a stability of “dynamic” In other cases, the real-world circumstances necessitate communication of an unknown code. There is no pre-coordinated agreement about this code, but there can be a pre-coordinated agreement that an unknown code is possible. Standards do not provide an explicit and distinct mechanism to support this notion; however, the notion is sometimes conflated in other mechanisms which dilutes the specification.

Figure 7.4: Extensibility and Stability Use in Specifications
For most internal value set bindings (at least for HL7 v2.x), the settings predominantly are “closed” and “static” (and for implementation profiles, extensibility has to be “closed”). A stability of “static” is appropriate for value sets where all concepts needed for the use case are known at the time of specification. These value sets may also have dependent concepts or those in which the value set is tightly-coupled to the underlying technical infrastructure; that is, the concepts have certain dependencies within the use case, and any change that is made has a significant and consequential impact on implementations. For example, if a value set for laboratory results defined a state machine using various status codes (preliminary, final, corrected, etc.), it would be unacceptable to allow another state to be defined outside the bounds of the specification. This example is one in which the value set codes are tightly-coupled to the technical infrastructure. A more subtle example is the definition of the abnormal flags (HL7 v2 Table 0078) that indicate the result interpretation. The code “H” indicates “above high normal” and “HH” indicates “above upper panic limits”. If an intermediate setting is needed, for example, “HU” for “very high”, then this concept should be defined as part of a new version of the interoperability specification and value set (and not as part of a local value set or a dynamic value set). Adding an intermediate value changes the interpretation of the existing result interpretations in the value set, which, in turn, is a patient safety issue (in some uses).
Other value sets that contain independent concepts can have a stability of “dynamic”. For example, ICD-10 codes could be updated and published periodically (as a new version or a new code system). This update is outside the scope of the published version of the specification that references the ICD-10 code system as a value set. Tagging the value set as dynamic, however, is a notification to implementers that the value set can change and that they should check for and make their updates accordingly.
There are circumstances in which it may be desirable to allow an unexpected code. An example might be when a new strain of a virus is detected that must be reported to public health agencies. A code for this virus could be established (without formal recognition of a code system steward) and reportable lab result messages sent immediately, even though the receiver may not know how to handle the new code. If the code can be handled by “generic” processing, however, a complete understanding of it by the receiver may not be necessary. Also, when the code and the associated concept are published officially, receivers that update to this new value set can then process this information in a meaningful way (if so desired). This circumstance is indicated in the “Operational Space” as an “Unexpected Code may be Sent”. As of this publication, none of the SDOs have a mechanism in their vocabulary machinery that supports this notion independently.
Vocabulary specification should provide a way to indicate whether a data element definition allows or disallows unexpected (unpublished) codes. The mechanism should not be conflated with existing mechanisms (i.e., Extensibility and Stability). Implementers must be able to distinguish concepts of extensibility and stability from the case of unexpected codes in operational environments. Such information would enable precise specifications and robust implementations. Systems could handle the “expected” unexpected code for data elements specified with this attribute and report a violation for data elements in which unexpected codes are not allowed. For most data elements, unanticipated and unexpected codes would not be expected (in well-defined specifications).

4.6.5 Profiling at the Code Level

Similar to, but not equivalent to, usage for data elements is the concept of usage for the codes in a value set. Vocabulary usage is a mechanism for defining and setting the scope of the concepts to be included, considered for inclusion (or exclusion), or excluded in a value set definition.
Table 7.11 defines usage indicators for profiling vocabulary. Required (R) usage indicates that the code must be supported (and thus can be used); Permitted (P) indicates that the code can be profiled to R, P, or E in a derived profile; and Excluded (E) indicates that the code must not be supported (and thus cannot be used) for the given element. The Permitted usage indicator is only applicable to constrainable profiles, i.e., it cannot appear in an implementation profile (it must become an R or an E). Permitted usage can be included in a closed value set (at the constrainable profile level). In this situation, the set of all known concepts are defined, but some concepts are left to be profiled at the implementation level based on local requirements/needs.
The assignment of the usage codes to define a value set presented here is similar to (but not quite equivalent) to the concept of min (=Required), max (=Required Permitted Excluded), and ignore (=Excluded) in HL7 V3.

Figure 7.5 indicates the relationship of vocabulary usage to the profiling hierarchy. The value set is deemed to be “scoped” (at the constrainable profile level). At the base standard level, all codes have an implied usage of Permitted. The base standard defines a set of concepts and the representative codes. The binding strength determines how the value set can be used in derived specifications. If the binding strength is “Required”, and if the concept that needs to be conveyed is available in the code set, then the code must be used. The use case analysis determines which codes are applicable for the element to which the value set is bound. An important point to make here is that the base standard would have defined a set of codes with associated concepts. A binding strength of Required means that the value set must be used; however, only the codes that are appropriate to use for the element to which the value set is bound should be specified in derived profiles. This analysis should be completed for every element to which the base vocabulary is bound. In practice, specification at this granular level rarely occurs in implementation guides.

Figure 7.7: Example Vocabulary Profiling 1
Figure 7.7 shows a vocabulary profiling example using an abbreviated value set definition. Starting with the base standard definition, a set of concepts and associated codes are defined. The Usage for all of the codes is Permitted, and the value set definition has “open” extensibility. This value set definition is equivalent to the sample vocabulary definition in Figure 7.6 (but the description and code system columns are omitted for brevity in Figure 7.7). The usage of each code in the value set is determined based on the use case analysis conducted during the development of a derived specification. In the Constrainable profile in Figure 7.7, the usage for codes “F” and “M” is profiled to Required; for “A”, “N”, and “O” the usage is profiled to Excluded; and usage for “U” is left to be decided in another derived specification (e.g., a local implementation). Furthermore, the specification authors decided that no additional codes can be added in derived profiles (Extensibility = “closed”), and that this value set is not suitable for revisions post publication of the specification (Stability = “static”). Next, Figure 7.7 shows that, at the implementable profile level, the local use case dictated that the concept represented by the code “U” was not needed, therefore, it is profiled with a usage of “E”. A different local use case could specify that the concept is needed, in which case the usage for the code “U” would be set to “R”.

Figure 7.8: Example Vocabulary Profiling 2
In the next example (Figure 7.8), the use case for the implementable profile warranted an additional concept represented by the code “X”. This extension is valid since the value set has Extensibility set to “open” in the constrainable profile. If the Extensibility had been “closed” in the constrainable profile, the code “X” could not have been added to the implementable profile (to be considered compliant with its parent profile).

Figure 7.9: Example Vocabulary Profiling 3
The example in Figure 7.9 shows that a new concept (represented by “Y”) was added in the constrainable profile, and another concept (represented by “Z”) was added in the implementable profile. The Base standard is “open”, which allows for the addition of code “Y” in the Constrainable Profile; likewise, the Constrainable Profile is “open”, which allows for the addition of the code “Z”. It is important to note that the extensibility is a construct that is in the specification space, so as long as the specification authors indicate that it is “open”, additional codes can be added as the use case is refined. This is the case even when the Stability is “static”, because this describes another dimension of specification; that is, whether the value set can be modified post specification by an external steward. In this example, the authors deemed this value set not to be modifiable post specification.

Figure 7.10: Example Vocabulary Profiling 4
Figure 7.10 demonstrates how the use of a dynamic value set might be defined in practice. Initially at the base standard level, not only is the concept domain known, but a particular code system is specified. An example might be the set of CVX codes for reporting immunizations. When published, the base standard specified codes ”01” through ”06”. It might be assumed that the binding strength and all code usages are defined as Required; however, generally no indication of this explicit requirement is given in the standards. It may also be assumed for this vocabulary definition that Extensibility would be “open”, and, for Stability either “dynamic” or “static” might be assumed (but again, typically no indication is given in the standards). Therefore, in Figure 7.10 all usages are initially shown as Permitted, Extensibility is set to ‘open’, and Stability is set to ‘?’ (unknown, but to be defined). In a constrainable profile (e.g., at the national level), it is likely that a newer version of the CVX code system exists, as years may have passed since the publication of the base standard and the development of an implementation guide, so the constrainable profile would reference the latest CVX code system. Figure 7.10 illustrates this possible change; the immunization represented by the code ”07” has been added to the code system. Stability for the constrainable profile is defined explicitly to be “dynamic”, which is an indication that post specification the implementer can expect this code system (implicitly a value set) to change. At the implementable profile level, another update has been made to the CVX code system: code “08” has been added. This change may have occurred by the time a particular implementation was installed, as the CVX code had been updated since the publication of the national level specification. Implementers should use the latest version of the code system available. Additionally, the implementers should be aware that subsequent revisions will be made and should plan accordingly. This situation is depicted in Figure 7.10 as a post specification revision; code “09” has been added. When the immunization message is transmitted, the version of the CVX code system used should be indicated (but it rarely is). Some data exchange standards support this capability (e.g., in later versions of HL7 v2.x with the message profile identifier), while others do not. In HL7 v2.x, the dynamic value set can be considered a profile component, and the sender can indicate support of a specific version of the value set.
Another situation to be aware of is the deprecation or status (e.g., made inactive) of codes in an external code system. In such a case, the usage of the code needs to be clearly indicated in the specification. In the previous example, what if code ‘03’ is made inactive by the external steward of the code system in the post specification space? Is it valid to continue to send the code? The answer depends on the value set specification tied to the anticipated use. If the value set is deemed to support newly administered vaccines, then the specification would indicate that inactive codes are now “excluded” and a new value set is created. However, if the use is for the messaging of historical vaccines, then the inactive codes are still valid (and therefore “required”). Separate value sets and bindings should be included in the specification to articulate the requirements precisely.
These examples illustrate the various ways in which a value set can be specified. The vocabulary profiling mechanism provides a flexibility utility such that a broad set of value sets can be specified.
An analysis should be performed for each coded element in the specification to determine which codes from a source code system are applicable for that particular element. Unfortunately, this level of definition usually does not occur in practice. Developers, therefore, must decide for themselves which codes apply to a particular element. For example, in many HL7 v2.x implementation guides, HL7 table 0203 (identifier type) is universally applied to every element that includes an identifier type with no profiling (i.e., HL70203 is simply referred to or is copied as is from the base standard). There are over one hundred identifier types, and in most cases only a few of the codes are pertinent to any given data element. Figure 7.11 presents one possible solution for specifying the appropriate level of detail.

Figure 7.11: Creating a Collection of Value Sets and Binding to a Data Elements
The Identifier Type in HL7 v2.x is bound to a number of data types and is used in higher-level elements. In a given specification, many data elements will use the Identifier Type for many different purposes. The base standard provides a set of codes for common identifier types that apply to a broad spectrum of identifiers. This set can range from a medical record number to a bank account number. For a particular element, however, only a few of the codes might be applicable.
At the base standard level all codes in a code system can be implicitly considered Permitted, thus giving the most flexibility for specification in derived profiles. An analysis must be performed for each element that uses the code system in order to ascertain which codes actually do apply. Figure 7.11 shows a sample list of codes for HL7 table 0203. It also indicates four elements to which this code system is bound in the base standard. For each binding, a value set is created that is shown in the form of a separate column. For the Patient Identifier List-Identifier Type (PID-3.5) element, analysis of the particular use case is necessary (e.g., analysis related to the Lab Results Interface (LRI) determined that support for the Medical Record Number (MR) and Patient External Identifier (PT) codes are required). The Driver’s License Number (DL), National Provider Identifier (NPI), and Social Security Number (SS) codes are Permitted, while the rest of the codes are Excluded. For the Patient Account Number-Identifier Type (PID-18.5) only the Account Number code is applicable. Value sets for Ordering Provider-Identifier Type (ORC-12.13) and Performing Organization Name-Identifier Type (OBX-23.7) are defined as well. In addition to specifying the usage for each code, other attributes for each element-specific value set are determined, such as the Binding Strength, Extensibility, and Stability. Essentially, the collection of value sets in Figure 7.11 are domains for the concept of identifier type, and elements can be constrained by indicating the domain.
The table in the lower part of Figure 7.11 shows examples of value set bindings that might appear in a specification (each row in the table would be in the associated element location in the specification). The upper part of the diagram shows the value set collection. Each column represents a value set and lists the associated attributes and vocabulary constraint usage for each code in the value set. Some of the attributes appear both in the specification and the value set collection, which allows for easy cross referencing (since they can be specified in separate documents).
The Binding ID is a qualifier to the Value Set Root Name (HL70203_USL) and, when combined, they provide the binding in the specification (e.g., HL70203_USL.3 is used to bind to the Identifier Type of the Ordering Provider element). The binding qualifier may be included as part of the binding definition in the specification (as shown in Figure 7.11) or it may not be included. If the qualifier is not included in the specification (profile), then the profile and the value set collection are separated, which means the value sets could be changed without requiring changes to the specification. The approach promotes effective management of updates, however, versioning must be accounted for and stakeholders need to be notified.
Although these value sets are shown to be bound to particular elements for a particular profile, value sets are defined independently in order to promote reuse of the value set. As an example, perhaps several value sets could be created from the administrative gender code system, and then the different value sets could be referenced in many specifications (not only HL7 v2.x, but any other specification based on other standards such as CDA and FHIR). This approach to value set reuse requires broader vocabulary management.

4.6.6 Vocabulary Profiling Mechanics

Profiling vocabulary is a multistage process including binding and the creation of value sets. The list below includes the tasks:

4.6.7 Profiling HL7 Tables

The base HL7 standard defines four types of tables:
Certain rules for these tables defined in the base standard must be adhered to in a constraint of the table. These rules are the starting point for placing constraints as described in the previously sections on vocabulary profiling.
User Defined Table: A user defined table provides an initial table identifier and in some cases suggested code values. These are recommendations and therefore place no initial requirements on the vocabulary definition. A specifier, in a message profile may use, extend, modify, or replace the suggested codes and descriptions. Once the vocabulary definition is defined, a specifier may bind the vocabulary definition to a data element and designate the binding strength as “required” as prescribed in Section X.X. That is, the specifier considers the data semantics associated with the data element, determines a suitable vocabulary definition, and declares that definition required.
HL7 Defined Table: An HL7 defined table provides an initial table identifier, code values, and certain base standard requirements. Code values defined in and HL7 table shall not be redefined in a message profile and if a concept needed for a use case is not defined, the table definition can be extended. Below is a list of rules for constraining HL7 defined tables:
Beyond the initial set of rules imposed by HL7 defined tables, constraints are applied as described in Section X.X.
External Tables: An external table is a vocabulary definition created, maintained, and published by another standards organization. A specifier may reference an external table and bind that table to a data element in a message profile. The base standard may bind a code system or a set of code systems to a data element. In cases of a CNE data type, this binding is the starting point for profiling.
Local Tables: The HL7 base standard provides no requirements or guidance for local tables. A local table is a table with a non-HL7 assigned table identifier and which contains a set of locally or site defined values. Local tables are typically used for elements with a CWE data type. During the process of profiling a specifier will create and bind local tables. The mechanisms described for profiling vocabulary in Section X.X shall be used to profile local tables.

4.6.7.1 Impact of Base Standard Data Types

Table X.X provides a summary of the initial requirements the HL7 v2 base standard places on vocabulary bindings. These requirements are the starting point for message profiles. In most cases, the responsibility of defining and specifying vocabulary requirements fall on the message profile specifier. In other cases, an initial set of requirements are given that can be further defined and constrained.

4.6.7.2 Relationship of Coded Element Based DatA Types and Flavors

The base standard provides a set of coded element data types for conveying coded data in message elements. This initial set covers only a small portion of specification possibilities. Using the concept of data type flavors and the vocabulary profiling mechanisms together provides a complete set of specifications. For example, the less restrictive “CWE” in the base standard can be constrained in many ways to precisely state the messaging and vocabulary requirements at a certain profile level. The data type definition determines the requirements on the presence of a code or not. Vocabulary profiling (binding parameters and vocabulary definition) indicates the requirements of code set and further constraint determinates. The base standard comingles these dimensions; the conformance methodology seeks to delineate the constructs in such a way that specifications and requirements can be clearly understood by implementers.

4.6.8 Summary

As should be evident from the information presented in this section, the specification, profiling, and use of vocabulary is a complicated and convoluted subject. An attempt was made here to provide the basic concepts (in a generic fashion) and to provide insight as to the factors that should be considered. Every standard approaches the specification and profiling of vocabulary in a different way; there is no common methodology or glossary of terms. The approach presented here is representative of one school of thought and by no means expresses a consensus viewpoint. For each implementation project, the vocabulary model and approach of the given standard have to be examined and applied. The level of granularity presented here illustrates leading practice for the definition of element-specific value sets; however, many of the standards don’t provide a rich enough vocabulary mechanism to enable achievement of this granularity. This issue should be addressed by all SDOs. The methods provided here are similar to a methodology that was proposed for HL7 v2.x and applied to the set of laboratory specifications developed as a Standards & Interoperability Framework project.
